"Bought this to save vs comcast rental.

Happy at first with high speeds.

Lately it freezes a few times a week requiring a power reset and dropping my security cameras.

Ive posted and emailed linksys and have yet to hear back.

Im regretting my purchase and will attempt to get some support before the warranty runs out.

Should have went with arris.

Review text: "Normally I lease a modem/router gateway from my cable company. I recently bought my own modem to save money on the monthly rental fee (which can add up to good savings). I got this for use with Spectrums service when I was in NC, but I recently moved to VA. I now have the Cox Gigablast Internet service, which is for Internet speeds of up to 1 Gbps. If you want to use this modem with Cox, the best it will support is the Cox Ultimate plan, which is speeds up to 300 Mbps downstream speed. That is plenty, but when it comes to data speed I like to stay on the bleeding edge of technology. So while this gateway will work for most people, if you want the highest speeds possible you will need to get a DOCSIS 3.1 compliant gateway.", "It was pretty easy to set up for me, and the wifi was decent. It started out pretty stable, but then became prone to disconnects (requiring a reboot) more frequently. It was far from unusable, but it was definitely not my favorite modem. I now use the Panoramic Wifi Router that comes with Cox service and I have no regrets. I will eventually buy another gateway, but it wont be this one."

Review text: I am not a particularly tech savvy person so I am always a bit apprehensive about installing new equipment.  I can tell you that an average person should be able to install this and get it running., The "hardest" -- at least the most time consuming -- part of the installation process was dealing with my cable company.  I have Comcast and they don't like you do swap out your internet modem without letting them know.  So I started out with a Comcast tech person on the phone and gave them all the information they needed and let them do what they thought was necessary to make this work with my internet service.  That part of the installation took at least a half hour and after that everything was easy., "The connections are as easy as my last Comcast-supplied modem and the Quick Start log-in information online was easy to follow as well.  I am cheap and have fairly slow internet service so cant speak to how quickly data flows but can say I havent had any problems.  And I like only having one piece of equipment to find room for, with the combination modem and wireless router."

Review text: I bought this used because I was sick of paying the rental fee, especially when I moved and switched from spectrum to xfinity and found that it was way more expensive. Clearly I should’ve read the reviews before buying it because this thing sucks. I live in an 1100 square foot apartment and my phone and laptop never connect when I’m in my office (and this is with an extender because I thought against all odds that maybe it was just because i was too far away from the router when this thing claims to have great coverage) The signal is consistently dropped and we reboot the router pretty much every day. My internet is 100 mbps and downloads were showing 67 with uploads at 54. There are times where I log onto an streaming app or FaceTime and as soon as I do that, the signal is dropped. It seems that the router can’t hold that level of bandwidth. Even when it does connect the streaming and video quality is very poor. I have issues streaming lectures and holding zoom meetings which is a huge problem since 95 percent of school is online now.  I just purchased an eero and a Netgear cable modem and I cannot wait until they show up.

Review text: "Normally I lease a modem/router gateway from my cable company. I recently bought my own modem to save money on the monthly rental fee (which can add up to good savings). I got this for use with Spectrums service when I was in NC, but I recently moved to VA. I now have the Cox Gigablast Internet service, which is for Internet speeds of up to 1 Gbps. If you want to use this modem with Cox, the best it will support is the Cox Ultimate plan, which is speeds up to 300 Mbps downstream speed. That is plenty, but when it comes to data speed I like to stay on the bleeding edge of technology. So while this gateway will work for most people, if you want the highest speeds possible you will need to get a DOCSIS 3.1 compliant gateway.", "It was pretty easy to set up for me, and the wifi was decent. It started out pretty stable, but then became prone to disconnects (requiring a reboot) more frequently. It was far from unusable, but it was definitely not my favorite modem. I now use the Panoramic Wifi Router that comes with Cox service and I have no regrets. I will eventually buy another gateway, but it wont be this one."

Review text: We ditched our cable providers gateway rental box for the Orbi CBR40 modem/router that is fast, reliable, and a breeze to set up. I think I called tech support once to ask them a dumb question. The guy was cool. Easy printer connection with WPS. It has a guest network so you don’t have to give out your password to randos. The satellite works perfectly-my son likes that he can hard-line his Xbox to it. I downloaded the Orbi companion app on my tablet and can see all the devices connected to my network. It has all the usual WiFi management tools, plus the you can purchase Netgear’s Armor protection through the app (it’s extra network security). You don’t need it, but It eases my mind cuz we have very young, and very old people using computers here. So, the Orbi app sends me notifications when it has blocked spam sites or detects malware on any of our devices, and shows me the website and WHO is trying to open it. The Orbi CBR40 also works with the Circle app if you want add some serious parental controls or screen time limits. I feel totally in control of my network for the first time. Highly recommend! AZCosmo12345

Review text: **UPDATE**  December 27, 2023, "It is now almost the end of 2023 and I am still having nothing but issues and headaches with this mesh router. All support is doing is having me do the same troubleshooting steps over and over again and then saying it is going to the developers to make a fix/change. Nothing is actually changing though with the product. It is still dropping connections randomly even when standing within a few feet of the router. The speeds are mediocre at best too. Consider the high price of this stuff you would think that it would work better and have better support. At this point I dont even think that I can recommend the NAS that I have from Synology due to the poor support. To me this signals a company that doesnt support their products well when there is an issue. Too bad it was so expensive because I am stuck with it.", I bought this to replace my Orbi Router that was getting a bit old. I already have a Synology NAS and I love it. The product has a great user interface (if you own their NAS you will be familiar with it) that is easy to use even if the multiple windows and menus take a bit to get used to. There is a lot that this device can actually do for you., My issue with it is that the wireless signal is constantly dropping. The 2.4 Ghz network on this is just fine but the 5Ghz network (also used for the mesh connection) is horrible. Constant disconnects from the wireless network on my tablets, phones, and computers. I even had it disconnect from wireless while I was standing two feet away from the router., I have been working with their tech support (seem pretty helpful in their desire to help but it is a slow process) which has been a little frustrating because it is a slow process. We have even swapped to a different router to see if it was a hardware issue and it has made no difference. I am still working with them to try to figure out the issue., Having worked in technology for over 15 years I have to say that this is the worst experience I have ever had with any router. I can highly recommend their NAS devices but there is no way that I would ever recommend anybody get one of their routers. Even if I was given this for free I would still not be able to recommend it. It has been a headache and time sink., Please just go with another company and save yourself the frustration.

Firewall features are rudimentary and just provide basic enablement and application based recognition., Where this device is severely lacking is in the radio WiFi controls. Review text: Other routers claim to have parental controls... not like this., "This router actually lets you control what your kids and do and not do right down to individual web sites (as well as grouping categories).  Its a little scary at first and you have to get used to the interface as there is a lot going on since you have so much control over the router, but just install SAFE ACCESS app and setup a few WEB FILTERS and assign them to your kids devices and finally take control.", "You dont have to subscribe to any external services or login to any websites or any of that nonsense.  This router is A DNS server (if setup correctly) and so all devices connected to it will use the router to get DNS information (URL to IP address conversion) so HTTPS encryption does not stop this router from blocking anything you want blocked;  like...", Want the kids off youtube?  Done!, Want the kids off social media?  Done!, Want the kids off Amazon?  Done!, Want the kids off Roblox?  Add it to the blocked list.... and.... Done!, Want the kids off game servers?  Add them to the block list.... DONE!, And blocking and white listing can be done by web filter groups which can be assigned to devices individually so, yes, you can setup each computer, smart TV, tablet, phone, whatever, with different access rights right down to what websites each device can access., The router has a ton of other features as well like Open VPN (so the entire network is on VPN) and media serving from any USB device that is connected to it and tons of other features, but for me the parental controls were the selling point.  The data privacy is awesome too.  This router blocks tons and tons of tracking websites and other data stealing and tracking stuff., "In addition you can set it up to update its DNS and other databases automatically, so all the databases are up to date.", My house went from a fight to keep the kids off of all the garbage on the internet to them actually doing school work on the internet and reading books and doing good things on the internet instead of watching morons on youtube dressed up like spiderman rolling around the grass at some park being weird or wasting all their time playing roblox learning nothing., One word of advice.  Do not let your kids know the account name and password to the router.  They will figure out the router address (192.168.1.1) and if they figure out the account info they will disable the blocking faster than anything., In addition the router has a really cool feature that allows the kids to make a page request, like if they visit a blocked site and they have a legitimate reason to have access they can submit an access request through the router (a web page that appears when blocking) and the parent can approve or reject the page after reviewing it (within the router)., And all this functionality exists on the router.  Unlike some routers where you have to have an account on the manufacturers website and possibly subscribe to some service (and maybe pay money) to have parental restrictions... nope... everything is on this router...nothing external., My old Netgear was a good router but it was terrible at blocking stuff as it did not act as a DNS server and everything slipped by using encrypted HTTPS since the router had no way to know what URL/IP was being accessed., If you have kids (and love them) get this router and tame the internet inside your house and save their minds from turning into social media and video game mush.

Review text: Other routers claim to have parental controls... not like this., "This router actually lets you control what your kids and do and not do right down to individual web sites (as well as grouping categories).  Its a little scary at first and you have to get used to the interface as there is a lot going on since you have so much control over the router, but just install SAFE ACCESS app and setup a few WEB FILTERS and assign them to your kids devices and finally take control.", "You dont have to subscribe to any external services or login to any websites or any of that nonsense.  This router is A DNS server (if setup correctly) and so all devices connected to it will use the router to get DNS information (URL to IP address conversion) so HTTPS encryption does not stop this router from blocking anything you want blocked;  like...", Want the kids off youtube?  Done!, Want the kids off social media?  Done!, Want the kids off Amazon?  Done!, Want the kids off Roblox?  Add it to the blocked list.... and.... Done!, Want the kids off game servers?  Add them to the block list.... DONE!, And blocking and white listing can be done by web filter groups which can be assigned to devices individually so, yes, you can setup each computer, smart TV, tablet, phone, whatever, with different access rights right down to what websites each device can access., The router has a ton of other features as well like Open VPN (so the entire network is on VPN) and media serving from any USB device that is connected to it and tons of other features, but for me the parental controls were the selling point.  The data privacy is awesome too.  This router blocks tons and tons of tracking websites and other data stealing and tracking stuff., "In addition you can set it up to update its DNS and other databases automatically, so all the databases are up to date.", My house went from a fight to keep the kids off of all the garbage on the internet to them actually doing school work on the internet and reading books and doing good things on the internet instead of watching morons on youtube dressed up like spiderman rolling around the grass at some park being weird or wasting all their time playing roblox learning nothing., One word of advice.  Do not let your kids know the account name and password to the router.  They will figure out the router address (192.168.1.1) and if they figure out the account info they will disable the blocking faster than anything., In addition the router has a really cool feature that allows the kids to make a page request, like if they visit a blocked site and they have a legitimate reason to have access they can submit an access request through the router (a web page that appears when blocking) and the parent can approve or reject the page after reviewing it (within the router)., And all this functionality exists on the router.  Unlike some routers where you have to have an account on the manufacturers website and possibly subscribe to some service (and maybe pay money) to have parental restrictions... nope... everything is on this router...nothing external., My old Netgear was a good router but it was terrible at blocking stuff as it did not act as a DNS server and everything slipped by using encrypted HTTPS since the router had no way to know what URL/IP was being accessed., If you have kids (and love them) get this router and tame the internet inside your house and save their minds from turning into social media and video game mush.

Review text: "I purchased the 6600AX. Wow what a cool router. I had purchased and returned SO many routers after having a G***** N*** Mesh System that was hacked (still sourcing the compromised IoT device but presumably from a Chrome plugin), compromising my security cameras and smart home and getting a virus on my MacBook. So far this is one of the best backend UI, Mobile App, ease of setup, and powerful range of any router Ive tried these past few months. Ive even considered getting firewall hardware devices combined with routers... However with this, I just need one device, no mesh or additional access points, and the coverage is mind blowing compared to what Ive tried.", This routers login is more like a PC, you can add and delete apps. The setup was a breeze and the complexity is however you make it., "My favorite part about this router is that I can add segmented networks. I have specific wifi for cameras, for IoT, for browsing, VPN, and work. You can specify how each network operates. AND each network runs on both 5ghz and 2.5ghz. I can add a Guest Network as well but havent needed it.", I had also purchased (and returned) another 6E router that was $350. The range did not reach my entire condo. Although only 1400 sq ft, almost every router on the market I tried needed another hub or WAP access point to get through a bedroom, bathroom, and living room wall. The RT6600AX is located in the farthest corner and reaches everywhere in my home. Although you can add either a 560 or 2200AC to the 6600AX to expand coverage, but I have not needed it with this one. A+++., The Synology RM (router manager program running the backend) is one of the most frequently updated brands on the market I believe. That was another big selling point for me. I feel like that is what makes devices safer and easier to manage., I also never review, but hoping that someone else frustrated finding a router who puts security at the top of their list, may find this helpful.

Review text: We upgraded to the Synology RT2600ac from an eero 6 system and wish we had done it much earlier. We're getting 3x WiFi speed and one-third the latency on our mobile devices. Plus, Synology control software actually provides useful tools to manage your network versus the eero approach of "what you don't know won't hurt you." The caveat here is that it's best if you have a reasonable degree of network literacy to take advantage of all the advanced features of the "DS Router" software. It helped that we were already users of Synology's best-in-class NAS solution so we were familiar with their control interface and UI., We supplemented the RT2600ac base station with 3 MR220ac mesh units since we have a large home (4,000 sq ft), and set-up of these mesh units was a breeze using the DS Router software. These mesh units can be connected via WiFi (like repeaters) or via Ethernet (like wireless access points) but they are much more powerful than repeaters or access points because they integrate with the base station as a true mesh with the same SSIDs for 2.4GHz and 5Ghz. This translates into much higher speed and lower latency than a traditional extended network., "Though I love my Synology system I have a couple of suggestions for improvement. First, unlike eero the Synology units are too large and ungainly to be wall-mountable, so our home definitely took an aesthetic hit. Second, device management needs to be improved: unlike eero there is no notification mechanism when a new device joins the network, and generally device discovery and identification is subpar, requiring a lot of upfront manual input to label all attached network devices. But Im sure that these issues will be addressed in future software releases."

Review text: I first used this older model modem in 2017 in Atlanta, and it worked great there with regular DOCSIS 3, Now that I am back in South Florida, I am finally using it with DOCSIS 3.1 and successfully also used LACP (802.1ax formerly 802.3ad) to go above the 1Gbps limitation of the 1GbE ports on the back of the modem., This modem does NOT have N-BaseT (aka 2.5GbE) on it.  So to go over 1Gbps, you need to employ a router that can do 802.1ax LACP to bond 2 separate 1GbE connections to achieve more than 1Gbps., I am doing that myself successfully after all these years now for the first time because my apartment complex upgraded my Internet connection (without my permission) to 1200Mbps., To do so, either find a router capable of LACP (in the software) as well as having more than the base 2 minimum ports (1 WAN, 1 LAN) to be able to do that.  I bought a 4 port 2.5GbE router with an Intel N100 CPU and intend to connect the LAN side to a 2.5GbE switch when I finally get one.  But on the WAN side I now have two ports and two cables going to the cable modem.  Just an idea for a way to make full use of this modem that IS capable of more than 1Gbps, just not with your average off the self consumer WiFi routers., Also, this is a pure cable modem and does NOT offer any routing or WiFi capabilities.  So you will need to get your own WiFi router, or like in my case, separate router and WiFi access point(s).

Review text: "I bought this used modem router to replace my unit provided by my ISP, Xfinity, to save the cost of the monthly rental. It is an excellent choice. Installs very well, with the help of an Xfinity technician, who ensures it is working properly and documented in the Xfinity internet system. The capability of this unit is advertised to provide download speeds up to 800 mbps, well beyond my requirements. It is designed to DOCSIS 3.0 standard, which is supported by Xfinity. I pay for 400 mbps download speed capability, and this unit easily supports that. It has a two-band capability, 2.4 GHz and 5 GHz. The lower band installs with an SSID of NETGEAR85, and the upper band installs with an SSID of NETGEAR85-5G. Your choice. I use both bands, depending on the device being supported. For example my network printer uses NETGEAR85, but my laptop computer uses NETGEAR85-5G. I have measured download speeds to my laptop of about 300 mbps, and upload speeds of about 25 mbps. These numbers are very satisfactory for my uses. I certainly recommend buying this unit instead of paying 100s of dollars for new modem router combos. Of coarse if you need the higher speeds the new units can provide, then go for it. But this unit meets my needs for an attractive price."

Review text: We had a Verizon Actiontec modem and a Linksys router that was about 8 years old. It worked well, however with the advance of smart TV, high powered wireless laptops and iPads the slowness was bothersome. The challenge was what to do and what to buy. All signs pointed to the Verizon ready Actionetc combined router and modem. The set up was a bit of a task, however no big problem. Within an hour we had all devices connected and off to the races. The speed is more than double the prior devices and the amplification is very strong compared to the prior devices. The annoying bumping or stream reloading is no more and the music and video speed and precision is top notch., We are connected to two Dell laptops, two iPad, two smart TVs, two iPhomes, and a smart Blue Ray player. All good., This is not compatible with Fios, so be forewarned. The general reviews, either at Amazon or the various internet review sites were accurate and helpful., 18 April 2015 Update, Nearly a year to the date of  purchace, it all shuts down. The lights show that all is OK, however nothing can connect and the signal goes in and out. I connected via ethernet and all OK. However still no wireless. My business is a IT platform, so  access is critical.  Fortunatly I have my old set up and have it going., I will try to reconfigure, however this is not a way to spend a Saturday morning.

Review text: I upgraded to this device primarily because my internet data provider, COX, was requiring a DOCIS 3.1 capable modem in order to upgrade or change my data service.  I had been using an earlier Netgear ORBI system that was only DOCIS 3.0 compatible.  After making the switch, the increase in my internet data speed was staggering.  I have the same COX data plan as before, Internet Ultimate with 500 MBPS download speeds, but my internet speeds have increased from 334.46 MBPS to 546.12 MBPS, an over 63% speed increase, with no change to my data plan.  Really outstanding.  I have a 2400 SF home so with the base unit and the satellite provided I have fantastic coverage.  As far as installation goes, it was pretty much unplug and disconnect the old modem, plug in and connect the new modem to my cable coming in, and set it up using the ORBI app on my phone.  Then I had to call COX tech support to have them enter the MAC Address and Serial Number of the new modem.  And with that I was up and running.  I am extremely pleased.

Review text: I have used this modem for about a year and 8 a months.  It functionally works, but I would not buy again., Pros:, 1.  set up and using on Centurylink network was easy, 2.  wifi broadcasting coverage in a 2 floor house works great, Cons:, 1.  it is highly difficult to use to schedule wifi access for family members.  I have tried over and over to restrict access for children so they cannot access at night so they go to sleep, but the scheduling features are super difficult to use.  Many aspects of the scheduler are counter-intuitive, so you have to use a time consuming trial and error method to find the magic combination of scheduling entries that might work.  You would think this is simple, but evidently it is not.  And the Centurylink product manual is zero help here.  At the end of the day, it wasted a lot of my time, was very difficult to use, and I could never really get it to work right., 2.  simple issues like software updates are also counter-intuitive.  Even when the modem update status indicates in red to "update firmware", a call to Centurylink tech support (another wasted couple of hours)  for their branded modem end up with tech support saying "it's already running the latest firmware.  you don't need to update it.", At the end of the day, I would think twice about buying this again.  The only high point is that it is very easy to get started and use on Centurylink network, but is severely lacking in the functionality that I want.

Review text: "Update #2 (11/14/2021): Im keeping this one short and sweet, as Ive updated and re-updated about 10 times now and its past the point of annoying. The CAX30 still randomly drops connections, even after updating the firmware as outlined in my previous update from June. While the drops in wireless connectivity are semi-rare, drops in connectivity with my wired devices are much more frequent. The persistent issues with the CAX30 are now unbearable, and Netgears lack of support and snail-paced firmware updates have really soured my once-favorable opinion about their products. No new firmware has been released since the last update I posted 5 months ago.", "Update #1 (6/25/2021): Reluctantly, I decided to give the CAX30 one last chance for redemption. And by that I really mean I procrastinated the return process past the eligibility date. Lucky for me, the latest automatic firmware update cleared up nearly all of the issues I was experiencing at the beginning! YAY! Wireless stability is substantially improved, and the internet connection is rock-solid. Unfortunately I still cant assign any IP address reservations under DHCP without having my devices being unable to reconnect via wired and wireless. Considering my devices can actually connect and stay online now, I will absolutely take that loss considering what Ive had to endure prior to the firmware update. If you own a CAX30 and are experiencing any of the issues I outlined in my previous update, check to make sure device is running firmware version 1.4.10.8.", "Original review and previous update: This is my fourth and final review update for the CAX30, all consolidated into one edit to prevent this from becoming a total mess. Two days after I posted my original review the CAX30 began to malfunction. This was absolutely gut-wrenching since I had just got done raving about how awesome it was. One day I woke up and noticed that none of my devices were connected to it, wireless and wired alike. The weird thing was my wireless signals were broadcasting and my SSIDs were available to connect, I just couldnt get anything to stay connected for longer than 2 seconds. After a few hours of troubleshooting with Comcast and Netgear, Netgear agreed to send me a replacement. The new CAX30 came the next day and it worked great for 4-5 days, but eventually it ended up having the same issue as my first model. I consider myself more than capable when it comes to networking, so I knew this was not user error. I mean, I have 2 CCNA certifications through the Cisco networking program. After multiple factory resets and some process of elimination, I came to the conclusion that the cause of all my problems were due to some sort of DHCP address reservation glitch in the CAX30. Even reserving a single IP address would cause the device to crash. Even after removing the settings, I still experience periodic hiccups with my wireless and wired connections. A device reboot will eventually solve the problem, although sometimes it requires multiple reboots to fix the problem for longer than 10 minutes. When this modem-router works properly, its impressive! The wireless speeds are super fast and the effective range is awesome (especially for an all-in-one device). I just cant look passed all the connection issues and recommend this product right now. Im praying a firmware update solves all of these problems in the VERY NEAR future, as Im already looking at different replacements while Im still within my return period.", "Bottom line... wait for the kinks to be worked out before you commit to spending $300 on this. If I own it for long enough for Netgear to fix it, I will be sure to provide another update. As it stands right now, the CAX30 is a buggy mess that cant handle the most simple setting changes. Until that happens, Ill be lowering my rating down to 2 stars (originally 5)."

Review text: We have owned 2 Motorola Router/Modem combos in the past, and they generally last around 4-5 years or so before kicking the can. This one is no exception, with 2 years of reliable service so far. We had a power surge somehow get past our surge protector and scramble it up once, but with a hard reset everything was good to go., The range is pretty good, providing tolerable speeds in our garage and out into our backyard. Our home is 2,500 square feet, with decent speeds in all of the rooms, the lowest points pulling 85mbps which I think is fair. The price easily goes up about $40 every time we need to re-purchase the next one, which is the only reason I dropped a star. Over $200 is a bit of a stretch for this, but at least it works how we want it to. Hope this review helps.

Review text: "I was recommended this combo by my parents who said it worked great. They got theirs before 2020. I took a look at the OS and how it worked for them and it seemed great; it had a nice, modern OS with good features and little to no latency. WiFi signal was awesome. Doesnt have an Intel Puma chipset and bufferbloat was basically non-existent. On paper and in action it appeared to be perfect. Got one myself in 2021 and my Internet would drop randomly. Contacted support and it was a pain to get a hold of them, but they eventually sent me another. That one ALSO booted me off the Internet at random. After testing some more and trying everything I could think of, I came to find that it wasnt my ISP or devices; BOTH WERE DEFECTIVE. Plugged in a new modem from another brand and the issues stopped immediately. I discovered this just in time for the manufacturer to (Motorolas exact words) ABRUPTLY AND UNEXPECTEDLY STOP SUPPORT. Chat doesnt work, email doesnt work, phone doesnt work. Youll see other reviews saying theyre waiting on a response; theyll be waiting forever because the customer support listed everywhere for modems/routers is straight up GONE. Through sleuthing in responses to reviews on other sites, I was able to get a hold of someone at another support line (which also takes forever) who said they couldnt give a refund and could only wait until more stock was available to replace mine which is who-knows-when. The last thing I want is another one of these; its been nothing but trouble from the start and Im now stuck with a $250 paperweight. Motorola used to be highly regarded, but from what Ive seen, not anymore. Steer clear unless you have ZERO other options, and also make sure that other option doesnt have a Puma chipset."

Review text: Others have commented on the way Arris seeks to simplify setup, and how it can tend to backfire. That sort-of happened with me as well; the app was less than hand-configurable, and I had to skip around with phone tech support both with Arris and with my ISP, which is NOT among those that Arris supports for their easy setup options., However, once those matters were resolved, the modem proved to supply a better range than I anticipated for both the 5 and 2.4 GHz signals. It’s been largely trouble free since, requiring no more than a handful of restarts in several months, most of them when it was still new. Evidently some software somewhere needed a patch or update, and seems to have gotten it., Yes, I understand the value and reason behind devices that don’t readily open themselves to user tinkering. But in my view it’s better to have the option and not need it, than it is to need it and not have it — as was nearly the case for me., My recommendation is that you contact or consult with your ISP first, and ensure ANY device you may be thinking of buying is on their official list of supported and recommended equipment.

Review text: After a decade my modem and router were starting to have problems connecting to the internet. I wasn’t having any issues streaming movies, video chatting, or data mining so I figured I didn’t need anything better. Then my internet started dropping out and I would have to do the turn it off and turn it back on procedure almost every week. When I checked the speeds on my old dual band router I was at 25 & 40 Mbps download. With this new router I am at 90 & 230 Mbps download which is a closer match to my Xfinity internet plan of 200Mbps download speed. I’m also excited that two devices are now one device! I have so much more room on my bookcase!, Install was okay. If you are using your mobile phone and not in a good service area, I recommend downloading the SURFboard app and your internet provider’s app prior to disconnecting your old modem. For Xfinity my steps were:, 1. connect the device to cables/ power, 2. give Xfinity the device’s HFC MAC ID (device is restarted remotely by company), 3. give SURFboard app the 2.4GHz name and Wi-Fi password, 4. login to SURFboard app’s WiFi management using admin & password then set your own, 5. change the names and passwords for the different network frequency bands, It was simple outside of the waiting time for everything to load on one bar from my cell phone. The biggest observable difference for me has been the map loading speed on Google maps. It’s not instant but it takes a few seconds to load now vs half a minute like before. The second best part is that I got it used for only $43. What an amazing deal!

Review text: I upgraded to this device primarily because my internet data provider, COX, was requiring a DOCIS 3.1 capable modem in order to upgrade or change my data service.  I had been using an earlier Netgear ORBI system that was only DOCIS 3.0 compatible.  After making the switch, the increase in my internet data speed was staggering.  I have the same COX data plan as before, Internet Ultimate with 500 MBPS download speeds, but my internet speeds have increased from 334.46 MBPS to 546.12 MBPS, an over 63% speed increase, with no change to my data plan.  Really outstanding.  I have a 2400 SF home so with the base unit and the satellite provided I have fantastic coverage.  As far as installation goes, it was pretty much unplug and disconnect the old modem, plug in and connect the new modem to my cable coming in, and set it up using the ORBI app on my phone.  Then I had to call COX tech support to have them enter the MAC Address and Serial Number of the new modem.  And with that I was up and running.  I am extremely pleased.

The rent-able modem from Xfinity worked just fine. He said go with Motorola instead if I wanted to buy one."

I have about 17 peripheral wifi based systems working in the house, from Rings cameras to garage openers to coffee machines and so on...this router can power it all with ease!

Just make sure to connect them to the 2.4Ghz network for the peripherals, unless its 5Ghz supported.

Review text: "Its been a few months since I activated my ARRIS Modem Wi-Fi device with Comcast, and it continues to work great.  I live in a small apartment and the Wi-Fi coverage is more than I need for my one-bedroom apartment.  I have different devises plugged into my modem; I can plug in up to 4 devices.  My PS5 shows a download speed of around 800 MBPS and my Xbox series S shows around 1 GB download speed using a category 7 ethernet cable.  As for the Wi-Fi, my smart phone is showing a download speed of around 200 MBPS and my RUKU ULTRA is also showing a download speed of around 200 MBPS.  The download speed will depend on the device youre using.  I have a regular RUKU, and the max download speed is around 90 MBPS.  This Modem Wi-Fi device has both Wi-Fi 5 and 4.  I have an older PS4, and it only picks up Wi-Fi 4.  When I first plugged in my Modem Wi-Fi device to my power outlet and cable outlet, it took a little while for it to turn on.  The 2 blue lights flashed for a while and then stayed on.  Soon after both lights started flashing and I didnt know what was going on, so I had to thoroughly read the owners manual and discovered it was updating the software.  It would have been nice if they had added that info to their activation instruction so we would Know whats going on.  Any way I waited a while for the update to finish and the blue internet light finally stayed on.  I went to my Xfinity App on my smart phone, and I followed the instructions to activate my new Modem Wi-Fi device.  I typed in the number on the bottom of my Modem, and I waited a little while and my internet light changed from blue to green.  I now have internet.  No need to call Comcast for activation.  To activate the Wi-Fi, I have to download the ARRIS App to my smart phone.  It is currently the blue and white App and link the App to my Modem Wi-Fi and followed the instructions to activate the Wi-Fi and the Wi-Fi light turned green.  I was able to change the password and Wi-Fi name on both Wi-Fi 5 and 4 using the App.  So far, its working fine no problems.  Its important that you use a category 7 ethernet cable or higher for high-speed internet.  2/24/24"

I have the 2100T also, the wireless range is a bit better on this one though.  Now I have two good routers.  Oh well...

Review text: My Internet plan with Xfinity supports download speeds up to 1 Gbps and upload speeds up to 100 Mbps.  I was typically getting download speeds of 950 – 975 Mbps but the upload speed was never above 25 Mbps even on my wired desktop systems.  I bought this Hitron CODA56 cable modem because it was one that Xfinity recommended in order to get the upload speeds I was paying for.  It replaced a four year old Netgear C7800 cable modem/WiFi router which only has 1 Gbps LAN ports vs the 2.5 Gbps LAN port that the CODA56 modem has.  I was not bothered by the CODA56 modem not having a wireless router as I have my own Multi-Gig wireless routers and Multi-Gig network switches (for wired desktop systems I use).  I have to thank Xfinity for letting me know about this supported modem because the others they listed were between $300 to $600 vs the $140 I paid for this one.  I wish I had waited a couple days before buying because it is now 20% off ($110) on Amazon, but even at $140, it is still quite a bargain given it’s specifications.  I activated the modem via the Xfinity app on my cell phone.  I have been using it for several days and I am impressed with the performance of this cable modem. Review text: We have owned 2 Motorola Router/Modem combos in the past, and they generally last around 4-5 years or so before kicking the can. This one is no exception, with 2 years of reliable service so far. We had a power surge somehow get past our surge protector and scramble it up once, but with a hard reset everything was good to go., The range is pretty good, providing tolerable speeds in our garage and out into our backyard. Our home is 2,500 square feet, with decent speeds in all of the rooms, the lowest points pulling 85mbps which I think is fair. The price easily goes up about $40 every time we need to re-purchase the next one, which is the only reason I dropped a star. Over $200 is a bit of a stretch for this, but at least it works how we want it to. Hope this review helps.

Review text: Original review: While not a deeply tech-minded person, I'm fairly capable when it comes to setting up my routers and devices.  This router came with no instructions relating to interface -- only a basic hardware-related 'quick setup' foldout;  I found my way on my own.  The unit does the job of ... routing ... perfectly well.  But the interface seems to have some serious bugs.  The interface also has a few weird misspellings, and errors in layout, making it look a bit 'spammy' (e.g., on Basic Settings page: "To create a Pre-Shared Key, enter at least eight (8) alphanumeric charaters in the test boxabove."  (sic)  This is weird and - and the textbox is  -- *below*, not above.)  The more serious problem: interface does not seem to allow you to change username ("admin") or PSK.  This seems an extremely serious issue.  Maybe I'm missing something, but I've been unable to find an explanation on the web.  Two stars just because the thing has a decent signal, and is relatively trouble free. Getting rid of this router., "UPDATE:  Yes, the documentation that came with the unit was inadequate, and the interface looks strange, is poor ... but (WHEW!) the potential security problem was ... NOT one.  I was indeed ... missing something.  (Something a better interface and documentation would have helped this noob avoid, but -- .)  Calling Actiontecs outsourced customer service -- on a late Sunday afternoon -- was a *positive* experience.  Apparently, (1) I needed to change both network name and PSK simultaneously - and (2) I had reflexively used a special character in my original effort to change PSK -  I guess I hadnt taken alphanumeric to heart. (an interface popup alerting me to this could have been helpful.  But enough complaining. I goofed.) Upping my rating to 3 stars (3 and a half feels right)."

Review text: "This modem/rooter was purchased to use with Century Link in Northern Utah.  We are so happy with our purchase. We ordered it on a Friday night.  It arrived Monday afternoon.  This unit was to replace a ZyXEL PK5001Z, that failed after several years of use.  A replacement would have cost over $100.  The Actiontec 300 Mbps Wireless-N ADSL Modem Router was a third of the cost.  It was very easy to install.  During setup, we encountered a problem trying to contect it with Century Link.  We called Actiontecs customer support.  An operator named Evan diagnosed our problem quickly and determined that it was a problem with Century Link.  Instead of just suggesting that we call them, Evan phoned Century Link and held a conference call between all of us.  He helped us learn that Century Link had misspelled our account name.  Together we were able to resolve the matter and complete the setup.  We would highly recommend this product and the company that supports it."

Review text: "I bought this modem in June because mine was many years old and I was experiencing sub-speed issues.  The first one I got turned out to be used and I couldnt activate it.  Amazon sent a replacement.  After many phone calls to Xfinity and  Netgear, I finally got it set up correctly, but with a marginal increase in speed. This whole process has taken me over 6 mos, so now I cant return the old modem.  Bottom line, it is worth it. Review text: I bought this model to replace an older, and very reliable, Arris Surfboard model that had been hit by a power surge during an electrical storm., "Ive given 5 stars on the basis of value for money, ease of setup, and overall performance.  Its compatible with my ISP, Xfinity.  This is a DOSIS 3.0 device, if you need the latest and greatest, there are a ton of 3.1 models available in the marketplace.  This model is smaller, lighter and capable of higher speeds than the older Surfboard model its replacing.", "I have lower-tier 100Mbps service, which is more than fast enough for the needs of my wife and myself, and this model checks all the boxes for us.  YMMV as they say, but unless theres a need for true Gig Speed service, this modem should be fast enough for most people.", Attach your incoming internet coax cable, plug in the power cord and the unit should power up.  The four lights on the front will begin flashing, and then go solid after a few minutes (be patient).  You are looking for a sequence of green-blue-blue-green lights which will indicate you are connected to the internet., "The simplest thing to do is to call your Internet Provider, let them add the modem to your account and provision (set up) the modem to their specs.  They will do this over the internet.  You will need to tell them the HFC MAC ID, which is printed on a label on the bottom of the box, along with the model number.  The customer service person should take things from there, you shouldnt have to do any further setup on your end.", You can attach your Wi-Fi router via the included Ethernet cable.  Hint:  if your Wi-Fi router has a Wifi On/Off button, you might turn WiFi off and on again.  This is different than power cycling the router, the router remains powered up while you turn WiFi Off/On.  This comes in handy if you encounter a message saying internet is not available, even though your WiFi router is up and running and visible on your laptop or tablet., "The instructions in the quick start document involved scanning a QR code, downloading an Arris App, downloading an Xfinity app, etc. in order to do a self-setup.  For me, it was much simpler just to call my provider and let them handle things.  Anyway, Im up and running with no issue, and at a bargain price IMO."

Review text: "Previously, I tried to install two other cable modems to replace my existing one. The first was an Arris, but a different model. I think it was refurbed or something because it had a dead ethernet jack. The second was a Netgear which would have worked if I only had one computer because it had a built in NAT. No use to me. Then I bought this model. Back to calling xFinity because if you already have a comcast modem, you CANNOT use the self install, own your equipment self activation. You must jump through hoops, endless voicemail redirects, and get someone who can provision your modem. They just need the model and mac address on the bottom. So after 9 hours, over 4 days of trying to get my own equipment working, it finally IS working. I pay for 800 blast, and this modem is limited to 686 mb I think. Regardless, the comcast modem which was here since 2006 (also an Arris, 16 years old) worked adequately (275 mb down) but was a little slow on the upload (9mb up). I have a 10 camera security system that streams to our phones so we needed better upload speed.  I would not have thought improving the download speed would have made a difference from 275 to 565 (my top download speed confirmed by 3 different applications and my router diagnostics) but holy moly, websites no longer load, they snap into place. Instead of take a second or two, they are there instantly.  Crunchyroll on my Roku was so slow I was ready to give up on the channel. It used to take 20 seconds minimum until I could see the high resolution thumbnails in the selection menu. Now it takes about 6 seconds.  Quite an improvement. Netflix, Hulu and Youtube now pretty much load instantly.", "So I CAN definitly recommend this modem, either to improve your speed if you have an upgraded plan, OR to get rid of the $14.00/month rental fee. FYI, I have paid over $2,800 to rent the $28.00 modem that I currently have in place. And the worst part is that when I upgraded to Blast pro 8 or 9 years ago, NO ONE TOLD ME that I needed to upgrade the modem. Comcast admitted that they forgot to let me know that a free modem upgrade came with the upgraded package. I was paying $50.00 a month more for nothing. Absolutely nothing."
